textDisplay: Montgomery Country RNAV 14 takes you down to 789 feet. The tower was 639 feet and is almost directly over the approach path of the runway. In addition to this, altimeters only need to be legally accurate to +- 75 feet. If this pilot was doing everything right, he could still have only been legally clearing that tower by less than 100 feet. Couple that with barometric and temperature correction (colder air makes you lower than indicated) - and he may have well been at the minimum altitude - and still hit that tower. The NTSB may find this as a contributing factor, and the RNAV 14 at KGAI may be amended.

textDisplay:
RUSSIA WHERE WARS ARE WON OR LOST ??
Wars are waged by older men
In battle rooms in countries apart.
Who call for greater firepower
And troops for the combat chart.

While out among the shattered flesh
The dreams of all have turned gray.
So young and determined their faces were
Till on the battlefield they lay.

Unable to overcome their pride
The politicians cast their vote.
For this or that or something else
As the rage of war sounds its note.

Wherever wars are won or lost
The soldiers fall like toys.
Down through history it remains the same
Most who die are hardly more than boys.

Like monkeys in a revolving cage
Man squabbles for the peanuts of power.
When will we rise above our greed
And become as a beautiful flower?

Death to death, dust to dust
The wrath of war is a hideous crime.
It‚Äôs our beast within that still prevails
As it has through the torments of time.

By Tom Zart

@Susan Fisher Amen Sister, Christ is the reason for the season! That's the way it use to be. It makes me very sad the way that children are raised today. They believe they should get all this material stuff, just because they asked for it...

If you had a safe home, a coat, few toys, some fruit and little candy around Christmas, we were doing good lol.

I remember my mom making the costume I wore for the Christmas pageant, I played a reindeer. Or just sending time with family or friends.

Having 4 siblings and growing up in the 60s, credit cards were rarities. Our Christmas was centered around church plays and family dinner. We each had 3 presents which usually included a coat, one toy and book. My parents spent only what they could pay in cash. Christmas was about Christ.
